# Summary

The **odds** of an event $A$ are defined by $$ \frac{\bbps{A}}{\bbps{A^c}}. $$ 
That is, how much more likely it is event $A$ occurs than it is that it doesn't.
Introducing evidence $E$ creates new odds as follows:
$$ \frac{\bbps{H\;|\;E}}{\bbps{H^c\;|\;E}} = \frac{\bbps{H}\bbps{E\;|\;H}}{\bbps{H^c}\bbps{E\;|\;H^c}}. $$

<div class="proof">

Note the following:
$$\begin{align*}
  \bbps{H\;|\;E}   &= \frac{\bbps{E\;|\;H}\bbps{H}}{\bbps{E}}     \\
  \bbps{H^c\;|\;E} &= \frac{\bbps{E\;|\;H^c}\bbps{H^c}}{\bbps{E}}.
\end{align*}$$
Divide two equations above for answer.

</div>

